{ This game (played at classical time controls) demonstrates several recurring motives from the 6. Bg5 Najdorf, such as white sacrificing pieces on e6 and b5 for a strong attack against black's uncastled king. Although the line initiated with 10. e5!? is objectively OK for black, an unprepared black player may soon find himself in a lost position if he does not know how to counter white's many threats. }
1. e4 { [%eval 0.03] } 1... c5 { [%eval 0.17] } 2. Nf3 { [%eval 0.03] } 2... d6 { [%eval 0.17] } 3. d4 { [%eval 0.08] } 3... cxd4 { [%eval 0.09] } 4. Nxd4 { [%eval 0.18] } 4... Nf6 { [%eval 0.3] } 5. Nc3 { [%eval 0.12] } 5... a6 { [%eval 0.29] } { Black opts for the Sicilian Najdorf. } 6. Bg5 { [%eval 0.0] } { My favorite line for white against the Najdorf. This often leads to sharp variations, and a lot of memorization is required (especially for black) to not lose to one of the critical variations. } 6... e6 { [%eval 0.0] } 7. f4 { [%eval 0.0] } 7... Qc7?! { [%eval 0.59] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Qb6. } (7... Qb6 { [%csl Gb2,Gd4] } 8. Qd2 Qxb2 { This "poisoned pawn" variation often leads to sharp positions as well. } 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. f5 Nc6 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Nxc6) 8. Qf3?! { [%eval 0.04] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bxf6. } (8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. Qf3 Nc6 10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Be2 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 f5) 8... Nbd7 { [%eval 0.27] } 9. O-O-O { [%eval 0.5] } { Preparing a long castle, and indirectly eyeing the h1-a8 diagonal in case black plays b7-b5. } 9... b5 { [%eval 0.42] } { Black goes for a system where Be7 is delayed. Thereby he gains a tempo in developing the queenside and launching an attack there, but not developing the bishop on f8 yet also has drawbacks. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gb5b4,Gc8b7] } (9... Be7 { This is perhaps the most common set-up for black, where black first develops the f8-bishop before advancing the b-pawn. }) 10. e5!? { [%eval 0.0] } { This critical move is theoretically OK for black, but only if he knows what he is doing... } { [%cal Gf3a8,Ge5f6] } 10... Bb7 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { Forced, as white was attacking both the knight on f6 and the rook on a8. This counterattack on the white queen allows black to capture on e5 on the next move. However, white gets a "free" move with his queen, as black is obliged to deal with the threat to his knight on the next move. } { [%cal Gb7f3] } 11. Qh3 { [%eval 0.0] } { The white queen takes aim at e6, setting up a knight sacrifice on e6. Due to black's move order, with the bishop still being on f8, this sacrifice will come with a tempo, thus gaining in strength significantly compared to lines where black has already plays Be7. } { [%cal Gh3e6,Gd4e6] } 11... dxe5 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { The best (and only) move. Moving the knight would allow white to crash through on e6, winning material. At least this grabs a pawn, and forces white to go for the sacrifice. } (11... Nd5? 12. Nxe6! fxe6 13. Qxe6+ Ne7 14. exd6) (11... Ne4 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qxe6+ Be7 14. Qxe7#) 12. Nxe6! { [%eval 0.0] } { Although this looks spectacular, many Najdorf opening books will tell you that this is "just a draw" with correct play. Unprepared black players however may have a hard time finding the correct moves at the board. } 12... fxe6 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { Forced, as otherwise white will have the initiative as well as extra material. } 13. Qxe6+ { [%eval 0.0] } { As mentioned, white exploits black's move order - with a black bishop already on e7, black would be able to defend against the upcoming attack more easily. } 13... Be7 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { Note that the move 13... Kd8 loses immediately due to the pin on the d-file. Now, how does white continue the attack? } (13... Kd8? 14. Bxf6+ gxf6 15. Qxf6+ $18 { And white wins the rook on h8. }) 14. Bxb5! { [%eval 0.0] } { Yet another sacrifice! Clearly white needs to prove that he has enough compensation for the sacrificed piece, and this move allows white to include the knight on c3 in the attack as well. White will be down two pieces, but the attack is overwhelming and black will soon be forced to return some of his material. } { [%cal Gc3b5] } 14... axb5 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { Forced - the threats against d7 and e7 are otherwise unbearable. } 15. Nxb5 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } { Again a forcing move, as white attacks the queen. Black does not get time to consolidate his material advantage. } { [%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] } 15... Qc6 { [%eval 0.0] } { Black would of course be happy to exchange queens and get rid of white's most dangerous attacker on e6. } 16. Nd6+ { [%eval 0.0] } { Preventing an exchange of queens for now, and stopping black's king from ever castling to safety. } 16... Kd8 $7 { [%eval 0.0] } (16... Kf8? 17. Qf7#) 17. fxe5 { [%eval 0.0] } { A rather quiet move. White is two pieces down, but black has to return some of his material already. Note that the previous moves for black were almost "automatic" and easy to find, and this position is the first point where black players need to know what they are doing, and where unprepared black players tend to go wrong. } { [%cal Ge5f6,Gg5e7,Gd1d8] } 17... Nd5? { [%eval 1.32] } { Mistake. Best move was Kc7. } { Black hopes to save his knight as well as the bishop on e7. However, greed is not advisable here, and with Kc7 and a couple more accurate moves he would be able to bail out to a draw. } { [%cal Ge7g5] } (17... Nxe5? 18. Qxe5 { And the threats against black's position remain. }) (17... Kc7! { This is one of the best moves for black, getting the king out of the pin on the d-file. This abandons the defense of the e7-bishop, but by capturing on e7 the white queen would also lose control of the a2-square, enabling counterplay by black. } { [%cal Gc7d6] } 18. exf6? (18. Bxf6 Bxf6 (18... gxf6 19. Qxe7 Rxa2 20. Nxb7 Ra1+ 21. Kd2 Qd5+ 22. Ke2 Qe4+ $10 { And black can force a repetition - white cannot give up a full rook on d1, while too many of black's pieces are hanging for black to play on for a win. } { [%cal Ge4d4,Ge4f4,Ge2d2,Ge2f2] } 23. Kd2 Qd4+ 24. Ke2) 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Rd4 $40) 18... Bxd6 $17) 18. Bxe7+ { [%eval 0.82] } { Black was threatening to play Bxg5+ himself, so this capture is forced. } 18... Nxe7? { [%eval 2.08] } { Mistake. Best move was Kc7. } (18... Kc7 19. a3) 19. Nf7+ { [%eval 1.95] } { The fork of the black king and the rook on h8 is convenient, but white is already too much material behind to bail out with a queen trade and Nxh8 now. } { [%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8] } 19... Kc8?! { [%eval 2.59] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Ke8. } { The black king tries to run to safety, but now the loss of the knight on e7 and the remaining threats against the black king are too much. } (19... Ke8 20. Nd6+ Kd8 { This would have forced white (me) to find a better move, such as Rhf1 to follow up with Rf7. } 21. Rhf1 $40 Ra5 22. Nf7+ Kc8 23. Qxe7 Rxa2 24. Kb1 Qa4 25. Qxd7+ Qxd7 26. Rxd7) 20. Qxe7?! { [%eval 1.9] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Rd6. } { White has regained one of the two invested pieces, and is still attacking the rook on h8. } { [%cal Gf7h8] } (20. Rd6 Qb5) 20... Rxa2 $132 { [%eval 1.87] } { Black hopes to set up an attack of his own, perhaps escaping with a repetition similar to the line illustrated after 17... Kc7 instead of 17... Nd5. In this position however white is just in time to exchange everything and end up in a winning endgame. } { [%cal Ga2a1] } 21. Kb1 { [%eval 1.99] } { Allowing a check on a1 would allow the black queen to deliver various checks across the board. } { [%cal Gb1a2] } 21... Qa4 { [%eval 1.93] } { Black threatens mate on a1, forcing white's reply. Note however that at this point, retreating the rook was also not an option anymore. } { [%cal Ga2a1] } 22. Qxd7+ $7 { [%eval 1.93] } { White initiates massive exchanges, which will ultimately lead to a winning endgame. } { [%cal Gd7a4,Gd7c8] } 22... Qxd7 $7 { [%eval 1.97] } 23. Rxd7 $7 { [%eval 1.86] } 23... Kxd7 { [%eval 1.82] } { White has the choice of capturing either rook. Which one should he take? } 24. Rd1+! { [%eval 1.55] } { A nice "Zwischenzug", to cover the d5-square and preventing black from winning the knight; carelessly capturing on a2 would drop the knight on f7 due to the fork on d5. Alternatively, white could capture on h8, and reach a similar winning endgame. Note that the text move seems to encourage black to capture the white knight with his king in two moves, but now white has a fork of his own to prevent this. } { [%csl Gd5] } (24. Kxa2? { [%cal Gb7d5] } 24... Bd5+ { [%csl Ga2,Gf7] } 25. b3 Bxf7 $17 { And black would emerge a piece up for a few pawns. }) (24. Nxh8 Ra8 25. Nf7 Ke6 { This would lead to a similar position to the game. }) 24... Ke7 { [%eval 1.95] } (24... Bd5? 25. Rxd5+ Ke6 26. Nxh8 $16) 25. Kxa2! { [%eval 1.92] } { The tactics work out for white, as black is unable to take on f7 without losing the bishop on b7 as well. } { [%cal Gd1d7,Ge7f7] } 25... Rf8 { [%eval 2.33] } { Black admits that capturing on f7 will lead to a hopeless position, but clearly this does not lead to a very pleasant position for black either. } (25... Kxf7 26. Rd7+ $16) (25... Ra8+ 26. Kb1 $16) 26. Nd6 { [%eval 2.02] } 26... Bxg2 { [%eval 1.77] } { Black regains one of three pawns he was down, but the queenside pawns are too much to handle. } 27. Rd2 $18 { [%eval 1.86] } { The white rook covers the second rank, after which white will start pushing the queenside pawns to victory. The remaining (white) moves are not necessarily optimal, but accomplish this goal. } { [%csl Gf2] } 27... Bc6? { [%eval 3.6] } { Mistake. Best move was Bf3. } (27... Bf3) 28. b4 { [%eval 3.47] } { Note that the knight on d6 nicely covers key light squares on the queenside, which are exactly the only squares the black bishop can defend. } { [%cal Gb4b5,Gb5b6,Gc2c4,Gc4c5] } 28... Rb8?! { [%eval 4.39] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Ke6. } (28... Ke6 29. b5 Bh1 30. c4 Rf1 31. Ka3 Rc1 32. Kb4 g5 33. Rf2 g4 34. Rf5 Bf3 35. Rh5) 29. Kb3 { [%eval 4.17] } 29... Ke6 { [%eval 4.04] } { Black needs to undermine the knight on d6 if he wants to stop white's plan of marching the queenside pawns. } { [%cal Ge6e5] } 30. Kc4 { [%eval 2.88] } { Aiming to support the knight on d6 with the king, and to support a white pawn march on the queenside. Note that the knight on d6 nicely covers c8, preventing black from driving the king from the c-file. } { [%cal Gc4c5] } 30... Kxe5 { [%eval 3.13] } 31. Kc5 { [%eval 2.83] } { Defending the knight and attacking the bishop with a tempo. Note the "bodycheck" towards the black king, preventing the black king from helping in the defense of the queenside. } 31... Ba8?! { [%eval 3.77] } { Inaccuracy. Best move was Bf3. } { A rather passive move, but other bishop moves are hardly any better. } (31... Bf3 { This would have at least prevented the activation of white's rook. } 32. b5 { White can for instance push his pawn to b6, play Kb5 and push the other pawn all the way to c7, and there is little black would be able to do to stop this plan. } 32... g5 33. Nc4+ Ke6 34. Rd6+ Ke7 35. Rh6 Be4 36. Ne5 Rf8 37. Nc6+ Kd7 38. c4) 32. Re2+? { [%eval 2.74] } { Mistake. Best move was b5. } { Driving the black king further from the queenside, and activating the last white piece. } (32. b5) 32... Kf4? { [%eval 4.08] } { Mistake. Best move was Kf6. } { Hoping for activity with the black king, but at the same time giving up the defense of his own kingside pawns. } (32... Kf6 33. b5 $16 g5 34. Rf2+ Ke6 35. c4 g4 36. Rf5 Rd8 37. Rh5 Rd7 38. Nf5 Kf6 39. Ne3) 33. Re7 { [%eval 4.07] } { White gains control of the seventh rank, attacking black's last pawns and supporting a b4-b5-b6-b7 pawn push. Black resigned (1-0). } 1-0


